      {
        "id": "f402596aed06af7cdaaf6b553a5a60410c8474eb",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 35,
          "name": "Gary Wu",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "gary.wu@gmail.com",
          "username": "gwu"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2018-01-23 18:04:22.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\nOne more high level comment:  it seems that we're doing a bunch of work putting the DCAE env config into the onap-parameters.yaml file, parsing and processing the values, and then using the values to update the onap_dcae.env file in the end.  Doing this then we have to be careful about properly quoting/escaping strings (i.e. for the private key), etc.\n\nIt is possible to just ask the user to provide onap_dcae.env directly?  It seems that this would be simpler to understand and also easier to diagnose when a bad value was provided.",
        "patchset_number": 5
      },
      {
        "id": "8f5e43c29d0d66d8b7edae3ed071968aa4b30511",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 137,
          "name": "Alexis de Talhouet",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "adetalhouet89@gmail.com",
          "username": "adetalhouet"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2018-01-23 18:27:43.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\n> It is possible to just ask the user to provide onap_dcae.env directly? It seems that this would be simpler to understand and also easier to diagnose when a bad value was provided.\n\nIt could be feasible, but user will still have to provide some params about the OpenStack on which DCAE is deployed, and the OpenStack on which DNS Designate is deployed, as I'm using those params to create the HEAT stack, and to manage DNS zone in DNS Designate.\n\nI'm not sure to agree it would be simpler. Often people don't understand those parameters, that's why I'm providing more insight about what they are, trying to regroup them. I understand there is a little bit of reading now, but hopefully it will get people to understand better how ONAP works. \n\nBut don't get me wrong, I fully agree with your comment regarding the fact there is a lot of work that has been done to retro-fit onap_dcae.env in onap-parameters.yaml and this is not the most efficient way. The config injection is being reworked in master.\n\nAt least with this, we have (almost) only one file to edit, and you're ready to deploy ONAP.",
        "patchset_number": 5
      },
      {
        "id": "7addde707a90a71fcbe0b8259d0abd57c0e82007",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 137,
          "name": "Alexis de Talhouet",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "adetalhouet89@gmail.com",
          "username": "adetalhouet"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2018-01-23 18:28:45.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\nAlso, to diagnose, one can go in the persisted data under /dockerdata-nfs/onap/dcaegen2/heat and look at the files there. Even one can edit the files in there, and restart the heat-bootstrap pod to retry.",
        "patchset_number": 5
      },
